<subSubSection id="B2A4657E944BFFF4F599626EFC216A39" pageId="11" pageNumber="494" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FA0136F5944BFFF4F599626EFC216A39" blockId="11.[151,1437,890,1349]" pageId="11" pageNumber="494">
<emphasis id="C8CAEAE7944BFFF4F599626EFE856BED" bold="true" box="[199,315,1142,1168]" pageId="11" pageNumber="494">Remarks.</emphasis>
Despite the rather widespread of 
<taxonomicName id="3DBE4D76944BFFF4F7EE626FFCEE6BED" authorityName="Goetghebuer" authorityYear="1933" box="[688,848,1142,1168]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Diamesa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="494" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="steinboecki">
<emphasis id="C8CAEAE7944BFFF4F7EE626FFCEE6BED" box="[688,848,1142,1168]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="494">D. steinboecki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the mountains of Europe, a detailed description of the adult male, the variability of brachypteric and macropteric forms at different altitude above sea level, was made only for the French Alps (Serra-Tosio 1971, 1973, 1974). Therefore, we found it expedient to give a brief re-description of males based on our material from the Pamir Mountains, where the species was found for the first time, and the Swiss Alps, as well as to add some data to the description of Serra-Tosio (1971, 1974) from the French Alps. Data of Serra-Tosio (1974) in our description are highlighted in bold.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
